{
    "title": "St Lucia profile - Timeline",
    "link": "https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19833217",
    "content": [
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "A chronology of key events:",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1501",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia sighted by Christopher Columbus."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/976/cpsprodpb/CC13/production/_127034225_gettyimages-1404620441.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Castries, the capital, boasts a natural deep water harbour. It was founded in 1650"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1635",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- The French establish a colony on St Lucia."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1660",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- The French sign a treaty with the indigenous Carib people."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1814",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- France cedes St Lucia to Britain following the Treaty of Paris; Britain proclaims the island a crown colony and brings in African slaves to work on the sugar cane plantations."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1834",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Slavery abolished."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1871-1956",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia a member of the Leeward Islands Federation."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1924",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia granted representative government."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1936",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia given a constitution providing for a majority of elected representatives in the legislative council."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1951",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia granted universal adult suffrage."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1958-62",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia a member of the Federation of the West Indies."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1964",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia ceases sugar cane production."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1967",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia becomes fully self-governing in internal affairs, with Britain remaining in charge of external matters and defence."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1979",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- St Lucia becomes independent with John Compton, leader of the United Workers Party (UWP) as prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1979",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Allan Louisy becomes prime minister after his St Lucia Labour Party (SLP) wins the general election."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1981",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Louisy resigns following a split in the SLP and is replaced by the attorney-general, Winston Cenac."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1982",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- John Compton returns to power after his UWP wins a decisive victory in the general election."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1987",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- The UWP wins a narrow victory in the general election."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1992",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- The UWP wins another general election."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1992",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Derek Walcott, a native of the capital, Castries, wins the Nobel Prize for literature."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1993",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Fall in the price of bananas leads to unrest and strikes by farmers and agricultural workers."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1996",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- John Compton resigns and is succeeded by Vaughan Lewis as prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1997",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Kenny Anthony becomes prime minister after his SLP-led coalition wins the country's biggest ever landslide in the general election."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2002",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "September - Tropical Storm Lili destroys about half of the banana crop. In some places entire plantations are wiped out."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2003",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - Parliament amends constitution to replace oath of allegiance to British monarch with pledge of loyalty to St Lucians."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2003",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "November - New criminal code passed, with controversial clauses on imprisonment for spreading \"false news\" and legalisation of abortion in some circumstances."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2004",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - Volcanic twin peaks - the Pitons - are declared a Unesco world heritage site."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Sir John Compton's last term",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2006",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "December - Sir John Compton's UWP wins general elections."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2007",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "April - St Lucia says it will re-establish diplomatic ties with Taiwan, 10 years after it broke off relations in favour of China."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2007",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "September - Prime minister Sir John Compton dies, is replaced by Stephenson King."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Return of Kenny Anthony",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2011",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "December - Kenny Anthony becomes prime minister after his SLP wins a snap general election."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2013",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "November - A Jamaican police team arrives to conduct an independent investigation into alleged extra-judicial killings by St Lucia's police in the 2010-11."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2014",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "May - St Lucia says it is planning to switch from the Privy Council in London to the Caribbean Court of Justice as its final court of appeal."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2014",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "June - A law criminalising gang membership - aimed at curbing the growing problem of gang-related violence - comes into force."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2016",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "June - United Workers Party beats Labour in early parliamentary elections. Allen Chastanet becomes prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2021",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - Philip Joseph Pierre  becomes prime minister after his St Lucia Labour Party (SLP) wins a clear victory in the general election"
            ]
        }
    ]
}